{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-02228/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-02228"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:22:28"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Lighting"]},"value":{"none":["low key"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A man sits with his legs crossed and his hands clasped toether."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-02228","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-02228"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1/1669c62e-54f2-45da-bde7-d70df5817c3c","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T15:47:28.708Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Reynolds is bemused by Alma claiming that he’ll lose the staring contest. Of course, given what happens in the film, it’s not really about a staring contest but a more general battle of wills. He seeks someone who can both dominate and care for him, and she’s more than willing to provide these opposing desires.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:761.1233480176212,93.81057268722465,482.6431718061673,636.2224669603524"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1/ed96444b-b1d9-4d8b-88a7-34995d35f79a","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T15:47:49.562Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>According to PTA, Daniel Day-Lewis was involved in selecting all pieces of set decoration for the film and the country house location to make it “his own,” going so far as to go through every book on the shelves (Film Inquiry, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW186573839 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QMnRQrulAUA\"><u>PHANTOM THREAD Paul Thomas Anderson Q&amp;A</u></a>”). In a deleted scene included in PTA’s short film consisting of moments excised from <em>Phantom Thread</em>, <em>For the Hungry Boy</em>, Reynolds can be seen reading <em>Splendours and Miseries</em> (1943) by Sacheverell Sitwell — a great gag that nods at Reynolds and Alma’s relationship together (ANNAPURNA, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW186573839 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lPwfENwnMlI\"><u>PHANTOM THREAD</u></a>”).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02228/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1489.1189427312775,17.92951541850215,423.5132158590309,1047.1035242290748"}}}]}]}]}